The paper deals with an algorithmic modification for finding single-source shortest paths in graphs with negative edges but no negative cycles. This falls under the category of graph algorithms and data structures, which is covered by cs.DS. The paper also involves probability and randomization, which are topics covered by cs.DM. The use of relaxation steps and negative cycle detection suggests that the paper may also be relevant to numerical analysis (cs.NA). The paper's focus on shortest paths and graph traversal makes it relevant to graph theory (cs.GR). Finally, the use of randomized algorithms and the mention of high probability suggests that the paper may also be relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
